attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a DDoS (Distributed Denial-of-Service) bot. It daemonizes itself, attempts to gain root privileges (`setuid(0)`), and connects to a command-and-control (C2) server to receive commands. The binary contains a large command processing function (`processCmd`) that parses attack commands such as `!UDP`, `!TCP`, `!HTTP`, `!VSE`, `!NTP`, `SLAP-OVH`, `!FLUX`, and `!STOP`. It implements numerous flooding functions (`sendUDP`, `sendTCP`, `sendHTTP`, `sendVSE`, etc.) to execute these attacks. The malware also interacts with watchdog timer devices (`/dev/watchdog`, `/dev/misc/watchdog`) to prevent the system from rebooting, a common tactic in malware targeting IoT devices.
